>Theodoro_Martus: GNRSTTU 3A GRUTT.NS +70 89
>Theodoro_Martus: GNRSTTU --  -70 19
#note this is probably the closest I came throughout the tournament to challenging a word and knowing for certain it would come off the board
>jd: EELRTTV 4A VETTE. +28 91
#note playing post-challenge is always one of the toughest parts of the game, especially against a speed demon like theodoro. I think this play is not quite right - quackle prefers LEVERET which I think ends up being a couple of points better. this allows him to fish right away by playing TEG (although NRSTU is not a highlight leave) or to clean up his rack by playing URGENT. in any case I'm in good shape.
>Theodoro_Martus: GNRSTTU E3 T.G +16 35
#note I did not know yucko, unfortunately.
>jd: IILMORR A1 MIR. +27 118
#note I did not know YUCKO#. given his leave it may have been better to block there with MILOR# or MIRO#. Assuming I would see either of them.
>Theodoro_Martus: ENRSSTU C2 EN.RUSTS +70 105
#note arrgh. how does this dude draw ES on a 2-tile draw. I honestly started to watch how he was drawing after this turn, even though the game before was annotated and you'd think someone would've noticed. I guess he just tends to get lucky against me.
>jd: FIILORR G1 RIF +24 142
#note FOIL at 10F sims a little better because it's more defensive. of course, I continued not to know YUCKO.
>Theodoro_Martus: JU 8A JU. +30 135
>jd: BILOORW I5 BOR.OI +19 161
#note all 15 of the top plays hook yucko. sheesh. if I'd known it was such a great word I would've studied it or something. this is pretty ugly.
>Theodoro_Martus: ?ADGINY 1G .eADYING +89 224
#note aaaargh. theodoro martus jr. strikes again.
>jd: AAFLNSW J3 FLAW +35 196
#note well, at least he didn't take the W play I set myself up for.
>Theodoro_Martus: ACDER K5 CEDAR +36 260
>jd: AGNSUWX 11I SWUNG +36 232
>Theodoro_Martus: IOP 12K POI +21 281
>jd: ?AEHLVX 13L HEX +40 272
#note I drew a blank!! but this rack is still really hard to figure out. I wanted to offload some of the high-point tiles to have a chance to bingo, but the only good play that gets rid of the X also gives him a big play. tough call. quackle says AVALE# sims even too.
>Theodoro_Martus: DIT 14M DIT +32 313
#note this dude just always seems like he has everythingdit
>jd: ?AALLNV 8K .L +3 275
#note well. here we go. I'm down a bunch with a blank and no great options and no play that scores more than 20. I'm proud that I thought of this here - given the unusual bag I have an excellent shot at drawing JAVELINA for 100, which should put me up a bit. he may also sacrifice some points to block my new lane. quackle also likes BACLAVA# which I have never seen.
>Theodoro_Martus: HOO L3 OOH +23 336
>jd: ?AAELNV A8 .AVELiNA +104 379
#note thank god. I actually drew an E.
>Theodoro_Martus: EO D7 OE +17 353
#note uh oh. do not want.
>jd: AEINNOP 10H P.A +14 393
#note well. the pool is very vowel heavy. if he has bingo tiles, then all that's left are probably vowels. and the Q. If he bingos my only chance is probably to stick him with the q. to that end, I show block the open I and minimize turnover. I only had about a minute to go through this logical thought process. unfortunately for me, I didn't know another collins word that would've saved me all this trouble - BACHA#. with plays on column M I would've scored enough to potentially outrun a bingo.
>Theodoro_Martus: AEILORS N1 .ASOLIER +72 425
#note how much credit do I give theodoro? did he see that he was creating a new Q spot for himself?
>jd: EEINNOT O7 NE +14 407
#note down to about 20 seconds. awesome. my plan worked. now I get to slowplay him and suck on the win if I can just get my plays down fast enough...
>Theodoro_Martus: AEQ 6M Q. +11 436
#note 
>jd: EINOT B11 TONE +17 424
#note all I had to do was play ONE instead of. unrelatedly, I missed LIONET# here which I knew because I actually played LIONETS# in my next game.
>Theodoro_Martus: AE M1 .AE +14 450
>Theodoro_Martus:  (I) +2 452
#note what a crushing defeat. and now I'm back to even again and I have 23 more games to try to build something out of this tournament. But at least I've learned another lesson, more specific than not challenging BUNE*...always make sure his last play didn't create another Q spot if you're trying to stick him.

On an unrelated note my lack of collins knowledge was probably as badly exposed here as in any other game where I didn't miss bingos.
